d","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":40,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":113,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Richard Rocliffe was born about 1342, in Roecliffe, Yorkshire, England, his father, Sir Richard Rocliffe, was 24 and his mother, Elizabeth Everingham, was 24. He had at least 4 sons with Rocliffe."},"et":{"abt 1342–Deceased":"umbes 1342–Surnud","1342–Male":"1342–Surnud","1344–Female":"1344–Surnud","1366–Male":"1366–Surnud","1368–1381":"1368–1381","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1372–Male":"1372–Surnud","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1368":"1368","1455":"1455","1366":"1366","1344":"1344","1320":"1320","1342":"1342","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1381":"1381","abt 1342":"umbes 1342","of Rocliffe, Yorksh., Engl.":"Roecliffe, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"abt 1342–Deceased":"noin 1342–Kuollut","1342–Male":"1342–Kuollut","1344–Female":"1344–Kuollut","1366–Male":"1366–Kuollut","1368–1381":"1368–1381","1370–Male":"1370–Kuollut","1372–Male":"1372–Kuollut","1320–Male":"1320–Kuollut","1320–Female":"1320–Kuollut","1368":"1368","1455":"1455","1366":"1366","1344":"1344","1320":"1320","1342":"1342","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1381":"1381","abt 1342":"noin 1342","of Rocliffe, Yorksh., Engl.":"Roecliffe, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"abt 1342–Deceased":"environ 1342–Décédé","1342–Male":"1342–Décédé","1344–Female":"1344–Décédée","1366–Male":"1366–Décédé","1368–1381":"1368–1381","1370–Male":"1370–Décédé","1372–Male":"1372–Décédé","1320–Male":"1320–Décédé","1320–Female":"1320–Décédée","1368":"1368"